00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:13.340
&gt;&gt; Sarah Werner:
Hello, and thank you.

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:14.640
Thank you all for coming.

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:17.660
And I want to say thank you
to Jesse for the invitation.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:20.560
And to the Chesapeake Chapter
and the Library of Congress

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:21.860
for making all of this possible.

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:27.330
I'm really looking forward
to this conversation.

00:03:27.330 --> 00:03:28.770
I should warn you that kind

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:31.400
of like what my scholarly
career has been.

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:33.490
This is less of a
straight-forward here I am.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:34.790
Here's my argument.

00:03:34.790 --> 00:03:36.090
We're just going to shoot
down towards the end.

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:37.640
It's a following of
thoughts that we're going

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:38.940
to sort of explore together.

00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:42.360
So I want to talk today

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:46.240
about what a feminist
history of printing could be.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:49.540
And what we lose by thinking
of it primarily in terms

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:52.690
of the history of
women printing.

00:03:52.690 --> 00:03:57.590
But first, I need to share some
context for these questions.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.020
Let's see if I can do this.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:02.240
Okay. A few years ago, I began
writing in earnest a guide

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:04.410
to how books were made
in the first centuries

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:05.710
of the printing press.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:07.860
Studying early printed books,
the one that Jesse mentioned.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.850
And there are fliers
on the back table.

00:04:10.850 --> 00:04:15.230
I had been teaching bibliography
and early modern book culture

00:04:15.230 --> 00:04:17.360
to undergraduates
for a decade by then.

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:19.770
And the whole time
I was teaching,

00:04:19.770 --> 00:04:22.040
I struggled to find
a suitable text

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:24.790
to help them understand
the common press.

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:27.830
Some guides were
entirely too brief.

00:04:27.830 --> 00:04:30.690
They would touch on imposition
and stop press changes.

00:04:30.690 --> 00:04:31.990
And then that was it.

00:04:31.990 --> 00:04:35.530
And then there was
Philip Gaskell

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:41.910
who wrote a wonderful book
full of details about printing.

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.180
So many details that
it is unfair

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:49.110
to call it an introduction
by today's 'standards.

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:51.840
For true beginners, the
book shares its knowledge

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:53.680
so authoritatively.

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:55.890
And densely that it's
hard to take hold of

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:57.820
and find a purchase on it.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.810
You have to understand
the full run

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:02.340
of press work before you
can really appreciate the

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:04.690
significance of format,
for instance.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:08.080
And yet there was no
helpful navigation system

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:11.450
to let you move around the
book as you might need.

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:13.390
I do love it, but.

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:15.450
And so you follow
Gaskell's lead.

00:05:15.450 --> 00:05:19.820
And if you read it enough times,
or if you have a patient teacher

00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:21.530
to guide you through it,

00:05:21.530 --> 00:05:23.760
you might absorb
enough of its subject.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:26.880
To return to it on
more equal footing.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:31.080
So I set out to write what I
refer to as "Baby Gaskell,"

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:35.630
a beginners' level exploration
of how the hand press worked.

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:39.740
And why it might be
good to know that.

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:41.670
Another piece of context.

00:05:41.670 --> 00:05:46.170
My classes were overwhelmingly
taken by women.

00:05:46.170 --> 00:05:49.010
They looked kind
of like this row.

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:51.590
I don't know about your
classes, if you teach.

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:54.990
But I would wager that
like classes in the English

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:58.140
or Library Science or History,

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:01.010
indeed like many
Liberal Arts courses,

00:06:01.010 --> 00:06:04.860
the student population
is more female than male.

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:08.790
Perhaps because of that and
perhaps because I am who I am.

00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:12.780
Which is someone who is never
not thinking about gender.

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.710
Our seminar discussions
often turned to speculations

00:06:15.710 --> 00:06:17.540
about gendered reading habits.

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:20.660
Or how print genders authorship.

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.700
And so as I was writing my
book, I started to worry

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:28.560
about how it was unthinkingly
replicating a gendered printing.

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:31.520
My first book was on Shakespeare
feminist performance.

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:33.430
Was I inadvertently
writing a book

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:36.510
that was printing in
[inaudible] press?

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:41.100
But since I was writing
about printing, not printers,

00:06:41.100 --> 00:06:44.050
where were my opportunities
to intervene?

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:47.920
Mine wasn't a work about
books or about the book trade.

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:50.390
So there was to focus
on authors or printers

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:52.340
or booksellers per se.

00:06:52.340 --> 00:06:55.440
Just a lot of information
about machines and processes

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:58.180
and discussions of
why it matters.

00:06:58.180 --> 00:07:01.130
So how could I bring my
investment in feminists' theory

00:07:01.130 --> 00:07:05.080
and practice to the
forefront of this work?

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:11.520
Twenty years ago, Leslie
Howsam published a brief

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:15.320
but pointed call to
arms in sharp news.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:19.950
In my view women and book
history is her advocacy

00:07:19.950 --> 00:07:22.340
for an explicitly
feminist approach

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:24.620
to studying book history.

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:28.470
But Howsam isn't interested in
excavating women's histories.

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:33.080
And she deliberately
sets that approach aside.

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:35.940
"Most of the women whose work
in the book's cycle has been

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:39.060
so painstakingly
discovered by researchers.

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:43.160
Has been, oop, has been
atypical individuals.

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:44.570
Outstanding anomalies

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:47.860
in a cultural field
dominated by men," she says.

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:51.550
I think she might be
overstating the assumption

00:07:51.550 --> 00:07:54.370
that such women were
entirely atypical.

00:07:54.370 --> 00:07:56.210
There's evidence that
in the first centuries

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:57.510
of the printing press.

00:07:57.510 --> 00:08:01.240
Women were an integral part of
the daily work of bookmaking

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.420
and bookselling, if
in small numbers.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:05.720
Although there's also evidence

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.990
that their numbers dropped
off in later centuries.

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:13.220
But her larger point I
think is still germane.

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:15.820
Adding to the scant
list of women known

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.470
to have been involved
in the book trades.

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:22.130
Only makes it slightly
less scant.

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:25.840
And such recovery work doesn't
necessarily help us confront.

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:30.280
The social and political forces
that shape women's lives.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:34.680
There is, I sometimes find it
necessary to say, a difference

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:37.880
between women and book history.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:41.990
And feminist approaches
to book history.

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:45.250
A catalogue of women
is not the same thing

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:47.390
as enabling a critical
examination

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:49.240
of the history of books.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:53.690
Or the methodologies we've
used to study that history.

00:08:53.690 --> 00:08:55.540
Returning to Leslie Howsam.

00:08:55.540 --> 00:08:57.740
Instead of fleshing
out the list of women

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.120
in the book trades, she writes.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:03.260
"I want to suggest that
book historians think

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:05.200
about how the book
has been implicated.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:08.340
In those structures of
masculine power and authority.

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:12.540
Known to feminist
scholarship as patriarchy."

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:15.480
For her, in other
words, the possibilities

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:19.170
for feminist book history lie
in working not with women.

00:09:19.170 --> 00:09:21.680
Necessarily, but with gender.

00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:25.130
The questions to ask are
not who made these books?

00:09:25.130 --> 00:09:28.830
But how are books
conceived of as gendered?

00:09:28.830 --> 00:09:33.530
As an illustration of this
avenue of investigation.

00:09:33.530 --> 00:09:37.070
Howsam points to the language
of conquest and courting used

00:09:37.070 --> 00:09:39.610
by collectors as one
potential avenue.

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:44.570
Such as this from
Richard Corell in 1930.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:47.980
"Books without points are
like women without beauty.

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:51.200
They pass unnoticed
in the crowd.

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:55.150
But books with points
excite immediate interest

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:57.530
in everybody, so to speak.

00:09:57.530 --> 00:10:01.530
Turns to gaze at them."

00:10:01.530 --> 00:10:06.300
As Howsam suggests in response,
"Perhaps we can also think

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:10.350
about the gendered possessive
not altogether unsexualized way

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:14.300
that book collectors have fixed
their gaze upon the object

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:16.630
of desire."

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:18.770
Some of you might want to
pat yourselves on the back,

00:10:18.770 --> 00:10:23.160
thinking that 1930
was a long time ago.

00:10:23.160 --> 00:10:26.680
But his attitude still shows
up in catalogues today.

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:29.490
Rebecca Romney has
been compiling examples

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:30.860
like this one.

00:10:30.860 --> 00:10:33.780
"perfect companion to curls.

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:36.700
Prettier copies are out there.

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:40.620
And even though I live in L.A.,
or maybe because I live in L.A.,

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:44.450
I'll take the girl
with depth of soul.

00:10:44.450 --> 00:10:48.700
Over the ubiquitous,
superficially attractive ones."

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:50.000
And that's from a catalogue-- .

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:51.300
Yeah, exactly.

00:10:51.300 --> 00:10:53.780
Just from a catalogue just
a couple of years ago.

00:10:53.780 --> 00:10:55.430
And this isn't the only one

00:10:55.430 --> 00:10:57.850
that shows how much the
male gaze is so with us.

00:10:57.850 --> 00:10:59.980
Rebecca has a whole
file of them.

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:02.950
I'm really grateful to her for
sharing some examples with me.

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:05.280
And if you happen to
come across examples

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:06.580
of these things in your work.

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:11.100
I'm sure Rebecca would really
love to know about them.

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:14.870
So. The tool Howsam uses

00:11:14.870 --> 00:11:18.790
to outside this gaze is
Jane Marcus' Theorization

00:11:18.790 --> 00:11:20.090
of Feminist Aesthetics.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:24.870
As Marcus works through it,
a feminist aesthetic is one

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:27.920
that values process
over product.

00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:31.550
One that avoids hierarchies
and exclusions.

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:35.230
For Howsam, this suggests a
feminist praxis of book study

00:11:35.230 --> 00:11:39.390
that downplays possession
in favor of utility.

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:43.020
Instead of favoring first
editions and famous authors,

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:46.620
it might instead think in
terms of less visible books.

00:11:46.620 --> 00:11:50.670
That gain meaning through
their social circulation.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:54.880
Perhaps, she suggests,
wryly, the way large numbers

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:57.920
of readers, both men and
women make use of books.

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:02.120
Maybe just as interesting in
the ways in which small numbers

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:04.140
of authors, publishers,

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:07.600
and collectors work
together to create fashion.

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:09.560
And preserve books.

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:14.800
Howsam's desire to focus on the
utility and social circulation

00:12:14.800 --> 00:12:17.610
of books aligns closely
with my own practice

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:19.670
and preference of
studying books.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:23.480
One that tends to focus on
things like [inaudible].

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:26.090
Very popular multi-lingual
phrase books

00:12:26.090 --> 00:12:28.090
and dictionaries
published across Europe.

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:33.540
In editions too many to count.

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:35.820
And many of you will
already know this about me.

00:12:35.820 --> 00:12:38.650
To express frustration
is what I do with things

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:42.950
like the obsessive tracking
of Shakespeare's first folio.

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:46.030
And the [inaudible]
goes, "Oh, my gosh, yes."

00:12:46.030 --> 00:12:48.290
[Laughter] It's not a
novel approach to the study

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:50.340
of books, by any means.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:52.790
Although it's still not
something that is often put

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.890
through an explicitly
feminist lens.

00:12:55.890 --> 00:12:57.920
But I want to look
a bit more closely

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:01.200
at how Howsam incorporates
Marcus' theory

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:05.350
of feminist aesthetics
into her own speculations.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:08.510
Much of the work Howsam
does draws on this excerpt

00:13:08.510 --> 00:13:14.400
from Marcus' 1988 book, Art and
Anger: Reading Like a Woman.

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:18.530
"This model of art," Howsam
quotes, "with repetition

00:13:18.530 --> 00:13:21.010
and dailiness at
the heart of it.

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:24.190
With the teaching of
other women the patient

00:13:24.190 --> 00:13:27.630
of one's cultural heritage
as the object of it.

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:31.950
Is a female poetic which
women live and accept.

00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:34.350
Transformation rather
than permanence is

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:35.750
at the heart of this aesthetic.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:39.710
As it is at the heart
of most women's lives.

00:13:39.710 --> 00:13:44.070
History is preserved not in the
art object, but in the tradition

00:13:44.070 --> 00:13:46.590
of making the art object."

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:51.340
It's this account of daily
making that leads Howsam

00:13:51.340 --> 00:13:54.060
to the observation that feminist
book history could attend

00:13:54.060 --> 00:13:56.640
to how books are used and
attend to books that are part

00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:59.740
of the everyday and ordinary.

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:03.430
What catches my attention
however is how much this

00:14:03.430 --> 00:14:07.590
scenario reminds me of
the act of printing.

00:14:07.590 --> 00:14:11.290
The repetition and
dailiness and patience

00:14:11.290 --> 00:14:13.030
of working the printing press.

00:14:13.030 --> 00:14:14.690
And setting the type.

00:14:14.690 --> 00:14:17.130
This is the unavoidable
nature of the actions

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:20.210
without which printing
wouldn't happen.

00:14:20.210 --> 00:14:24.700
And Marcus' emphasis on making
the art object resonates

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:27.680
strongly for me with
analytical bibliography.

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:30.210
Especially as I've spent
the last years writing

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:31.510
about how books are made.

00:14:31.510 --> 00:14:34.230
And teaching students how
to recover that process

00:14:34.230 --> 00:14:38.580
through the physical evidence
left behind in material texts.

00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:42.850
So where does Marcus get
this model of art from?

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:46.540
Here's the full passage
taken from Still Practice:

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:50.510
A rested Alphabet Toward
a Feminist Aesthetic.

00:14:50.510 --> 00:14:52.940
The 1984 article that is one

00:14:52.940 --> 00:14:55.950
of the three pieces forming
the basis of her book.

00:14:55.950 --> 00:14:58.580
As an aside, I should note
that throughout this talk,

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:01.480
I tend to quote from articles
that books were based on.

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:03.190
Largely because as an
independent scholar,

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:06.640
articles are a lot easier
for me to access than books

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:08.470
and that I think
is also something.

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:09.770
That's part of thinking

00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:12.650
about what a feminist
history might be.

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:16.080
Lipking, you would
know, in this quote,

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:20.220
refers to Lawrence Lipking's
piece Aristotle's Sister.

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:23.610
In which he argues for a
feminine poetics of abandonment.

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:28.860
An important foil for Marcus in
this I know, lengthy, passage.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:33.540
"We could imagine another
aesthetic, call it Penelope's,

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:36.180
which grew out of
a female culture.

00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:40.190
Lipking says that
Arimneste, Aristotle's sister,

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:43.830
'cannot compete, of course,
with her brother's tradition.'

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:47.380
Penelope's aesthetic
does not wish to compete.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:51.120
This anti-hierarchical,
anti-theoretical,

00:15:51.120 --> 00:15:53.980
not aggressively exclusionary.

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:57.340
A real woman's poetics is
a poetics of commitment.

00:15:57.340 --> 00:16:00.510
Not the poetics of abandonment."

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:05.800
Above all, it does not separate
art from work in daily life.

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:09.110
Penelope weaves her
tapestry by day.

00:16:09.110 --> 00:16:11.800
And takes it apart by night.

00:16:11.800 --> 00:16:14.080
Could Aristotle destroy
his lectures

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:17.120
and start over again each day?

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.310
This model of art
with repetition

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:22.690
and dailiness at
the heart of it.

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:25.750
With the teaching of other
women the patient craft

00:16:25.750 --> 00:16:27.490
of one's cultural heritage.

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:31.210
As the object of it
is a female poetic

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:33.870
which women live and accept.

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:36.420
Penelope's art is work.

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:39.050
As women cook food
that is eaten.

00:16:39.050 --> 00:16:41.340
Weave cloth that is worn.

00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:44.390
Clean houses that are dirtied.

00:16:44.390 --> 00:16:48.300
Transformation rather than
permanence is at the heart

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:51.060
of this aesthetic as
it is at the heart

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:54.310
of most women's lives."

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:58.280
The ellipses in Howsam,
all the bits of the weaving

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:02.280
that she has unpicked from
this argument are all the parts

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:04.700
that are about Penelope.

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:07.410
I can see why she would
worry in her brief piece

00:17:07.410 --> 00:17:09.250
that it would be a distraction.

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:11.080
That it would take
too much explanation

00:17:11.080 --> 00:17:13.800
to give it proper context.

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:15.600
But that this passage is

00:17:15.600 --> 00:17:19.870
about Penelope undoing her
weaving every night makes it

00:17:19.870 --> 00:17:24.470
for me all the more
about printing.

00:17:24.470 --> 00:17:26.420
As an aesthetic about printing,

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:30.250
Marcus' account here
works shockingly well,

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:33.110
even better than
with the emissions.

00:17:33.110 --> 00:17:36.010
If you've ever done even
the smallest bit of work

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:40.680
on common presses, you know
that it is entirely a process.

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:45.970
Not only of repetition, but of
breaking down and starting over.

00:17:45.970 --> 00:17:49.240
Dab ink on the balls, work
the ink, dabbing on the form.

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:51.010
Dab, work, work, dab.

00:17:51.010 --> 00:17:53.710
And at the end of the say, take
the stuffing out of the balls.

00:17:53.710 --> 00:17:55.390
Soak the leather
and next morning,

00:17:55.390 --> 00:17:57.430
reassemble and start again.

00:17:57.430 --> 00:17:58.730
Pick the piece of type up.

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:00.030
Place it in the stick.

00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:02.430
Place another, place another,
put the line on the stone.

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:04.660
Put another, put
another, tie it up.

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:05.960
Tie up another page.

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:07.260
Tie up another.

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:08.560
Lock it up, print it off,

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:10.640
distribute the type
back into its boxes.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:12.620
Start all over again.

00:18:12.620 --> 00:18:15.110
Place the paper on the tin
pan, fold the frisket down.

00:18:15.110 --> 00:18:16.410
Fold the whole thing down.

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:17.710
Roll it under the [inaudible]
and pull the bar [inaudible].

00:18:17.710 --> 00:18:19.010
And once more, pull again.

00:18:19.010 --> 00:18:20.310
Roll it out.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:21.610
Open the frisket,
take the paper off.

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:22.910
Put the paper on.

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:24.210
Fold it down, fold it down,
roll, pull, roll, pull.

00:18:24.210 --> 00:18:25.510
Roll, pull, open,
hang the paper.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:32.590
Go home. Come back the next
morning and do it all again.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:36.060
Penelope's weaving
disappears each night.

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:37.900
And a printer's work does not.

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:42.160
Since the printed paper
remains and heats in gatherings.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:47.530
But the unmaking of the press's
parts are a key components

00:18:47.530 --> 00:18:51.050
to keeping the work going
and the debtors at bay.

00:18:51.050 --> 00:18:55.490
And if you are as I am,
committed to the belief

00:18:55.490 --> 00:18:59.460
that every single copy
of a text is unique,

00:18:59.460 --> 00:19:01.900
thanks to inevitable
printing variance.

00:19:01.900 --> 00:19:05.340
And the vagaries of
its individual life.

00:19:05.340 --> 00:19:08.080
Then an awareness of repetition

00:19:08.080 --> 00:19:11.070
and variation makes
an aesthetic based

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:15.360
on Penelope's weaving
all the more compelling.

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:21.940
So let's talk about actual hand
press printing for a moment.

00:19:21.940 --> 00:19:24.710
If I'm only interested in
the mechanics of printing

00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:27.030
as the only thing
really my book was about.

00:19:27.030 --> 00:19:29.660
Need I think about
gender at all?

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:31.640
Well, yes.

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:33.490
Always yes.

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:36.700
But especially yes in
Renaissance England.

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:41.230
Where the word press was term
that could be used both to refer

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:44.990
to printing but also
to a physical pressing

00:19:44.990 --> 00:19:47.230
of a man into a woman.

00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:53.030
That is an act of sexual
penetration and deflowering.

00:19:53.030 --> 00:19:55.370
The author might
be a man in print,

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:59.040
but he is not pressed
as a lady is pressed.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:02.060
It is the book that is
pressed, and the author

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:03.920
who does the pressing.

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:07.000
An ambiguity, an anxiety
that Wendy Wall works

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:11.030
with in her 1993 book,
The Imprint of Gender.

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:13.790
But there need not be
winks and nudges for sex

00:20:13.790 --> 00:20:15.860
to be brought into the topic.

00:20:15.860 --> 00:20:20.950
Lisa Maruca's 1993 Bodies
of Type is the rare piece

00:20:20.950 --> 00:20:23.970
of scholarship that
reads printers manuals.

00:20:23.970 --> 00:20:28.090
Not as transparent
printing lessons.

00:20:28.090 --> 00:20:31.290
But for their rhetorical
and ideological practices.

00:20:31.290 --> 00:20:35.120
In her hands, we are
brought to see the gendered

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:38.360
and sexualized language
that is repeatedly drawn

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:40.410
on in these manuals.

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:43.050
Take for instance this passage

00:20:43.050 --> 00:20:46.640
from Joseph Moxon's
1683 Mechanic Exercises

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:48.900
on the Whole Art of Printing.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:51.190
In which he describes
the component parts

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:53.520
of a letter mold.

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:56.340
"When his stick of
letters is thus transferred

00:20:56.340 --> 00:20:59.030
to the male block,
he claps the middle

00:20:59.030 --> 00:21:01.410
of the male block
into his left hand.

00:21:01.410 --> 00:21:04.120
Tilting the feet of the
letter a little upwards

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:07.090
so that the face might
rest upon the tongue.

00:21:07.090 --> 00:21:08.450
And then takes about the middle

00:21:08.450 --> 00:21:10.870
of the female block
in his right hand.

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:13.960
And lays it so upon the
male block that the tongue

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:18.090
of the male block may fall into
the tongue of the female block.

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:19.420
[Laughter] So that when the knot

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:22.410
of the male block is lightly
drawn towards the knot

00:21:22.410 --> 00:21:23.710
of the female block.

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:27.000
Or the knot of the female block
lightly thrusts toward the knot

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:28.300
of the male block.

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:34.040
Both knots shall squeeze the
letter close between them."

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:38.280
We are so habituated to
the description of plugs

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:42.330
and other objects being
described as female or male.

00:21:42.330 --> 00:21:44.570
That it might not occur to
you to note this passage

00:21:44.570 --> 00:21:45.890
when reading through Moxon.

00:21:45.890 --> 00:21:49.220
I don't think I did until I
started reading Lisa's work.

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:50.860
And of course, the language

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:53.640
of the human body
is used throughout.

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:59.130
Pieces of type have feet,
shoulders, heads, bodies.

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:03.730
But Maruca points out that such
language emerges in this period.

00:22:03.730 --> 00:22:07.650
The OED traces the use of
male and female as adjectives

00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:10.760
for objects with
projecting of hollow ends.

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:13.250
To the late 16th century.

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:17.080
The first entry for male gauges
is Moxon's passage earlier

00:22:17.080 --> 00:22:19.510
in this section about
male gauges falling

00:22:19.510 --> 00:22:21.870
into female gauges.

00:22:21.870 --> 00:22:27.130
These are not just bodies, but
bodies that are being sexed.

00:22:27.130 --> 00:22:31.220
And John Smith, 1755,
The Printer's Grammar.

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:33.030
The laboring bodies
have disappeared

00:22:33.030 --> 00:22:34.770
as Maruca points out.

00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:36.880
But a rigid gender
hierarchy remains

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:39.920
to govern appropriate
typeface choices.

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:44.120
The strong upright Roman face
should be used for the main text

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:48.290
with a delicate flowing
italic, used only to decorate

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:50.590
within the Roman context.

00:22:51.770 --> 00:22:56.460
Maruca's project in the
work of print, the 2007 book

00:22:56.460 --> 00:22:58.730
into which her article
is incorporated is

00:22:58.730 --> 00:23:02.350
to consider the many ways
in which the acts and agents

00:23:02.350 --> 00:23:05.270
of bookmaking create an
ideology of authorship

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:07.850
that is gendered
and politicized.

00:23:07.850 --> 00:23:09.440
But what I want to
call attention

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:13.800
to is how effectively she puts
down the wishful thinking.

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:17.860
That we can treat printer's
manuals as transparent windows

00:23:17.860 --> 00:23:21.110
onto early modern
acts of printing.

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:24.810
So much of what we know
about how books were made

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:26.810
in the hand-pressed period.

00:23:26.810 --> 00:23:29.910
Are based on Moxon and Smith.

00:23:29.910 --> 00:23:31.470
And the [inaudible].

00:23:31.470 --> 00:23:34.230
Bibliographers draw on their
work to produce the works

00:23:34.230 --> 00:23:36.550
that become the basis
of our study.

00:23:36.550 --> 00:23:40.330
Works like those of
McCarrow and Gaskell.

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:46.130
How do we escape the masculinist
underpinnings of our knowledge?

00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:49.300
Is it useful here to think
about Dianna Taylor's notions

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:51.210
of archive and repertoire?

00:23:51.210 --> 00:23:52.510
To deal with the tensions

00:23:52.510 --> 00:23:55.300
between reading ideological
texts and the desire

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:57.840
to recover acts of printing?

00:23:57.840 --> 00:24:02.040
Taylor's concepts fleshed out
in her 2003 book are based

00:24:02.040 --> 00:24:03.610
in performance studies.

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:06.020
And geared towards
recovering Latin American

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:07.680
cultural histories.

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:10.260
And while I sometimes get
impatient with her dichotomy.

00:24:10.260 --> 00:24:12.650
I also find it generative.

00:24:12.650 --> 00:24:17.820
Here's a quick and superficial
description of her concepts.

00:24:17.820 --> 00:24:22.130
Cultural memory is contained
both in written archives

00:24:22.130 --> 00:24:24.860
and in bodily repertoire.

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:28.040
When the dominant history of
conquest has been preserved

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:30.250
in archival documents.

00:24:30.250 --> 00:24:32.390
Where can you find
indigenous culture

00:24:32.390 --> 00:24:34.400
in history in its own voice?

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:37.990
In the embodied history
of experience passed

00:24:37.990 --> 00:24:42.210
down from one generation of
survivors to the next, she says.

00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:47.400
Theater, dance, gesture, all
can be valid forms of knowledge

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:52.790
and history and capture what
written documents cannot.

00:24:52.790 --> 00:24:54.820
So if printers' manuals are part

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:56.860
of the written archive
of printing history.

00:24:56.860 --> 00:24:58.930
And if they have an
ideological slant.

00:24:58.930 --> 00:25:02.920
As Maruca's readings says
they do and as all things do.

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:06.600
Can we counter that bias in the
physical repertoire of printing?

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:09.570
Is a feminist praxis
of printing history one

00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:11.980
that emphasizes doing
over reading?

00:25:11.980 --> 00:25:17.670
Although printing practices
have changed over the centuries,

00:25:17.670 --> 00:25:20.410
scholar/printers have
long been interested

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:22.700
in early techniques
of bookmaking.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:24.340
Debating finer points.

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:25.810
Rebuilding presses.

00:25:25.810 --> 00:25:29.040
And relearning what
was once known.

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:31.810
There might not be an embodied
repertoire that's been handed

00:25:31.810 --> 00:25:33.950
down to us in a direct line

00:25:33.950 --> 00:25:37.070
from London's printers
in the 17th century.

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:40.730
But there is an active
repertoire living in bodies,

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:44.200
printing on wooden
hand presses today.

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:48.650
Bodies or people who are often
eager to share what they know.

00:25:48.650 --> 00:25:51.610
It isn't only muscle memory
involved in being able

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:54.520
to pull the bar, lower the
[inaudible] just smoothly

00:25:54.520 --> 00:25:55.950
and hard enough.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:57.970
But a physical knowledge
that is expressed

00:25:57.970 --> 00:25:59.780
by doing rather than writing.

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:03.460
And that repertoire of
knowledge through doing.

00:26:03.460 --> 00:26:07.610
Is a central part of exploring
how hand press printing worked.

00:26:07.610 --> 00:26:08.910
On the other hand.

00:26:08.910 --> 00:26:12.470
And this is no small
point when we're thinking

00:26:12.470 --> 00:26:15.240
about equity and inclusion.

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:18.490
Books can be significantly
more accessible

00:26:18.490 --> 00:26:21.680
than bodies and printing
presses.

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:25.180
There are only so many
printers and so many presses.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:28.520
Printers deserve to be
paid for their time.

00:26:28.520 --> 00:26:32.990
Replica presses are much
too heavy to travel.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:35.920
How many educators work
at a place where printing

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:38.870
on a common press can
easily be incorporated

00:26:38.870 --> 00:26:41.370
into your classroom practice?

00:26:41.370 --> 00:26:45.360
How many educators are active
printers or have access to funds

00:26:45.360 --> 00:26:50.150
to pay printers a decent fee
for working with their students?

00:26:50.150 --> 00:26:53.310
But books can be
priced affordably.

00:26:53.310 --> 00:26:56.430
I know they are not
always, but they can be.

00:26:56.430 --> 00:26:59.210
They can be resold
for even less.

00:26:59.210 --> 00:27:01.100
They could often
exist in digital form.

00:27:01.100 --> 00:27:05.140
Maybe accessible to a wide range
of abled and disabled users.

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.850
You can take them home and
revisit them on your own time

00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:10.600
if you didn't understand what
happened in the classroom.

00:27:10.600 --> 00:27:15.350
And you can keep them until
you've used them to pieces.

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:18.750
Not that any of us would be
so careless with our books.

00:27:18.750 --> 00:27:22.310
There are good reasons why we
teach history from the archive

00:27:22.310 --> 00:27:23.990
and not through repertoire.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:27.080
And among them the
documents are more conducive

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:29.240
to how universities are set up.

00:27:29.240 --> 00:27:31.910
And we should never forget
the material conditions

00:27:31.910 --> 00:27:34.170
that inform what we do.

00:27:34.170 --> 00:27:37.770
If we're historians and
bibliographers in fact.

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:41.030
Our training should mean that
we always keep those material

00:27:41.030 --> 00:27:45.970
conditions at the
forefront of our thoughts.

00:27:47.610 --> 00:27:49.500
Let's go back to
where this started.

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:51.580
What is a Feminist
History of Printing?

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:54.400
And what do we lose by
thinking of it primarily

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:57.650
as the history of
women printing?

00:27:57.650 --> 00:28:00.450
I've had to think about my
own feminist praxis outside

00:28:00.450 --> 00:28:02.240
of recovering women's history.

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:05.420
Because of my recent focus
on explicating the workings

00:28:05.420 --> 00:28:07.900
of presses and libraries.

00:28:07.900 --> 00:28:10.490
But maybe that's
only my problem.

00:28:10.490 --> 00:28:12.570
Why not look in the
archives to recover

00:28:12.570 --> 00:28:15.570
who the early women
printing in France were?

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:17.890
Why not compile a
catalogue of books printed

00:28:17.890 --> 00:28:20.090
by women in early America?

00:28:20.090 --> 00:28:24.560
How is that not a feminist
practice of book history?

00:28:24.560 --> 00:28:26.730
It can be.

00:28:26.730 --> 00:28:29.140
I can think of plenty of
works of printing history

00:28:29.140 --> 00:28:31.500
that I would say are
doing feminist work.

00:28:31.500 --> 00:28:34.590
And I can absolutely
think of works

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:37.320
about equivalent
modern technologies.

00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:40.190
Like Marie Hick's recent
Programmed Inequality

00:28:40.190 --> 00:28:43.740
that are field changing and
profoundly feminist ways.

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:46.020
And that are consistent with
this sort of work that we do

00:28:46.020 --> 00:28:47.740
in the history of printing.

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:51.930
So I'm not saying that
such work isn't valuable.

00:28:51.930 --> 00:28:54.140
But it can't be the
only feminist work

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:56.620
that print historians are doing.

00:28:56.620 --> 00:28:59.670
Let's talk about recovery
history for a moment.

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:03.150
Why we do it and
what we're missing.

00:29:03.150 --> 00:29:05.570
Today's drive to
recover the history

00:29:05.570 --> 00:29:08.000
of women's activities
comes primarily

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.440
out of the feminist
movement of the early 1970s.

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:16.400
We need to tell her story, not
his-story, urged Robin Morgan.

00:29:16.400 --> 00:29:20.870
And it's no coincidence that
the word her story first appears

00:29:20.870 --> 00:29:22.830
in print as part of the byline

00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:26.750
for Morgan's [inaudible]
Good-bye to All That.

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:30.690
The editorial she published
in the January 1970 issue

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:33.030
or Rat Subterranean News.

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:34.900
Which was taken over
by women in protest

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:38.970
of the male editorial
staff misogyny.

00:29:38.970 --> 00:29:43.260
If Morgan was a woman
inspired to commit "herstory,"

00:29:43.260 --> 00:29:44.760
as she signed herself.

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:46.920
Her readers were ready for it.

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:49.910
Ready to stop believing the
stories they'd been told

00:29:49.910 --> 00:29:52.760
about what was good
behavior and what was bad.

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:56.120
What counted and what didn't.

00:29:56.120 --> 00:30:00.160
Let it all hang out,
Let it seem bitchy,

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:01.920
catty, dike-y, [inaudible].

00:30:01.920 --> 00:30:06.220
Frustrated, crazy, nutty,
frigid, ridiculous, bitter,

00:30:06.220 --> 00:30:10.970
embarrassing, man-hating,
libelist, pure, unfair, envious,

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:16.160
intuitive, low-down,
stupid, petty, liberating.

00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:20.310
We are the women that
men have warned up about.

00:30:20.310 --> 00:30:23.050
[Laughter]

00:30:23.050 --> 00:30:24.540
That drive to look back

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:27.990
at the stories we've been
told and to see the gaps.

00:30:27.990 --> 00:30:30.760
Where we've been
removed is powerful.

00:30:30.760 --> 00:30:32.400
Honest to god, every
time I read through that.

00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:35.620
I get the, I get
the shivers, right?

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:38.680
We were all these, all along.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:41.780
That witch in the corner
of your eye is the widow

00:30:41.780 --> 00:30:43.320
who won't marry.

00:30:43.320 --> 00:30:46.860
That scandalous behavior is
running a profitable business

00:30:46.860 --> 00:30:48.350
on her own.

00:30:48.350 --> 00:30:52.410
We are the women that
men have warned us about.

00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:56.130
And we have always
been part of history.

00:30:56.130 --> 00:30:59.790
It's powerful to feel that
rush of connection to the past.

00:30:59.790 --> 00:31:05.330
Recovering the history of women
printing does that for us.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:06.880
And what about the history

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:09.930
of enslaved women
in the book trades?

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:14.450
Or the history of indigenous
people and the printing press?

00:31:14.450 --> 00:31:16.830
Where's the queer
history of printing?

00:31:16.830 --> 00:31:19.490
The trans history?

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:22.320
You tell me you've
recovered the history

00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:25.810
of a previously hidden
group in the book trades.

00:31:25.810 --> 00:31:29.260
And I will ask you
about another group.

00:31:29.260 --> 00:31:33.380
Where are they and what's
the connection between them?

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:36.560
If we are recovering history
in order to make it all

00:31:36.560 --> 00:31:39.310
of our history, we are
faced with the choice

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:44.430
between either ignoring who
is excluded from that all.

00:31:44.430 --> 00:31:46.950
Or searching for
more and more firsts.

00:31:46.950 --> 00:31:51.890
And more and more histories to
make the past more equitable.

00:31:51.890 --> 00:31:55.320
But you cannot simply keep
adding recovered histories

00:31:55.320 --> 00:31:57.710
and think that it will
take care of the problems.

00:31:57.710 --> 00:32:02.970
Of our overwhelmingly white
male field faces today.

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:04.690
It's an odd thing, isn't it?

00:32:04.690 --> 00:32:06.080
That I started off by talking

00:32:06.080 --> 00:32:08.830
about how largely
female my classroom.

00:32:08.830 --> 00:32:12.120
Yet here we are nearing
the end, and I'm talking

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:14.760
about how male the field is?

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:19.980
But in this book history
follows the pyramid of academia.

00:32:19.980 --> 00:32:23.060
And libraries and book dealing.

00:32:23.060 --> 00:32:25.900
In which there are large
numbers of women studying.

00:32:25.900 --> 00:32:29.440
And working at the
lower levels of a field.

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:35.350
But the higher the status of the
job, the fewer women there are.

00:32:35.350 --> 00:32:40.730
How does recovering history
level today's playing field?

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:43.410
Here's another question
to think about.

00:32:43.410 --> 00:32:47.070
What do you want the future of
printing history to look like?

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:49.020
Who do you want to be printing?

00:32:49.020 --> 00:32:50.930
Who do you want to
be studying it?

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:52.540
Who are writing the stories?

00:32:52.540 --> 00:32:54.770
What sort of technology
is part of this process?

00:32:54.770 --> 00:32:59.460
When I suggested our field
is facing problems today

00:32:59.460 --> 00:33:01.330
because it is white and male.

00:33:01.330 --> 00:33:04.130
What I want to focus on
is how much knowledge

00:33:04.130 --> 00:33:07.650
and experience we are missing.

00:33:07.650 --> 00:33:11.400
And how unsustainable
this pattern is.

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:14.670
Think about Dorothy
Porter at Howard University

00:33:14.670 --> 00:33:19.110
and how she saw what the white
librarians in her era did not.

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:22.820
That the Dewey classification
system collapsed any possibility

00:33:22.820 --> 00:33:25.920
of blacks being seen
through the lens.

00:33:25.920 --> 00:33:28.500
Wait, classes the
possibility of them being said,

00:33:28.500 --> 00:33:33.630
seen outside the frame of
either slavery or colonization.

00:33:33.630 --> 00:33:36.220
[Inaudible] What about
Paula McDowell's revelations

00:33:36.220 --> 00:33:39.530
about women's participation
in public print

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:41.270
and debate in the 18th century?

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:44.650
How could we even begin to
think about book history

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:50.230
as a discipline without
Elizabeth Eisenstein?

00:33:50.230 --> 00:33:54.450
Our world would be immeasurably
poorer without them.

00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:58.820
But when I look at my shelves of
books about hand press printing.

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:02.110
They are overwhelmingly
authored by men.

00:34:02.110 --> 00:34:04.530
When I look at the
companions and readers we used

00:34:04.530 --> 00:34:05.830
to teach book history.

00:34:05.830 --> 00:34:08.000
The sections that touch

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.350
on technologies,
those about printing.

00:34:10.350 --> 00:34:13.730
And those about digital books
are overwhelmingly authored

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:15.230
by men.

00:34:15.230 --> 00:34:19.580
When I look at my own citation
practice in my own book.

00:34:19.580 --> 00:34:23.120
A book in which I was
consciously trying not

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:25.360
to repeat this bias.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:27.150
They are overwhelmingly male.

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:31.740
This is the part where I
shame myself thoroughly

00:34:31.740 --> 00:34:33.920
and profoundly.

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:38.220
I was really horrified
when I counted.

00:34:38.220 --> 00:34:44.340
I realized, look at those cards.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:51.810
The future of printing
isn't going to be books

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:57.440
on wooden presses written
by and about white dudes.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:02.320
The future of printing
and the future

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:08.330
of printing history is going
to be machines and computers

00:35:08.330 --> 00:35:10.950
and technologies that
haven't been invented yet.

00:35:10.950 --> 00:35:14.710
And they'll be used to make
texts and to circulate them

00:35:14.710 --> 00:35:16.500
and to circulate the texts.

00:35:16.500 --> 00:35:18.970
That are about the
making of the texts.

00:35:18.970 --> 00:35:20.690
And they're going to
need to be written

00:35:20.690 --> 00:35:23.850
by a much broader
range of people.

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:27.750
If our field is going to not
only be relevant and exciting.

00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:30.350
But if it is going to exist.

00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:33.060
Bibliographers are a
small group of scholars,

00:35:33.060 --> 00:35:35.210
heavily indebted to the past.

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:38.370
The past when women could barely
squeeze through the entrance

00:35:38.370 --> 00:35:40.880
into [inaudible]
and Bowers' classes.

00:35:40.880 --> 00:35:45.200
And I really wish Barbara Mower
were here to tell us about that.

00:35:45.200 --> 00:35:49.790
And it's a past of male
scholars and female typists

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:55.030
that still determines how we
understand and describe books.

00:35:55.030 --> 00:35:59.050
So why do we need a feminist
praxis of printing history?

00:35:59.050 --> 00:36:01.280
We need it so we can thrive.

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:04.480
We need it to expose
why we do what we do.

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:09.120
And to invite more people in to
help us understand the field.

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:14.760
Let's turn back one
more time to weaving.

00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:17.580
What does thinking about
weaving get us in striving

00:36:17.580 --> 00:36:20.190
for a feminist praxis?

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:23.710
The key part of the
Penelope story is not simply

00:36:23.710 --> 00:36:25.490
that she weaves.

00:36:25.490 --> 00:36:29.790
But that she takes apart
her weaving every night

00:36:29.790 --> 00:36:32.630
and then starts again
the next morning.

00:36:32.630 --> 00:36:35.710
It's the willingness to
dismantle paradoxically.

00:36:35.710 --> 00:36:37.140
That makes her art an aesthetic

00:36:37.140 --> 00:36:40.380
of commitment and
not abandonment.

00:36:40.380 --> 00:36:42.980
Abandonment would
be walking away.

00:36:42.980 --> 00:36:45.350
Commitment is sticking it out.

00:36:45.350 --> 00:36:50.150
The problems, the errors, the
suitors who try to control you.

00:36:50.150 --> 00:36:53.150
You fix the turned
letters, the dropped lines,

00:36:53.150 --> 00:36:56.460
the last minute insertions.

00:36:56.460 --> 00:37:00.340
Commitment is also dealing with
the harassment of the suitors

00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:01.640
and we call them suitors.

00:37:01.640 --> 00:37:04.510
But let's make no mistake,
they aren't courting her.

00:37:04.510 --> 00:37:06.720
They're courting
Odysseus'' wealth.

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.720
Penelope is using the
strategy at her disposal

00:37:09.720 --> 00:37:12.700
to delay an impossible situation

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:17.060
until she can assert
her own will.

00:37:17.060 --> 00:37:21.110
Weaving is an art and
an everyday activity,

00:37:21.110 --> 00:37:23.680
but it is also a protest.

00:37:23.680 --> 00:37:27.570
A scholarly practice
based on weaving means not

00:37:27.570 --> 00:37:30.460
that we erase our writing.

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:32.870
You know, which we already do.

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:37.600
It means that we keep our minds
open up to error and revision.

00:37:37.600 --> 00:37:39.600
That we lead with a willingness

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:42.600
to relearn what we
thought we knew.

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:46.390
That we decenter
ourselves as experts.

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:50.880
And situate ourselves in a
community of questioners.

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:54.260
And it means too that
we make ourselves

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:56.220
and our knowledge accessible.

00:37:56.220 --> 00:37:59.850
Are we publishing in
locked away spaces?

00:37:59.850 --> 00:38:03.790
Or are we participating in the
open commons of conversation?

00:38:03.790 --> 00:38:06.480
Are we willing to learn
and respond to changes

00:38:06.480 --> 00:38:08.510
in the world around us?

00:38:08.510 --> 00:38:13.280
If we insist that printing
history is one thing only.

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:16.670
That bibliography
is one thing only.

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:21.370
That a book is words on paper,
we are locking ourselves

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:23.820
out of the conversation.

00:38:23.820 --> 00:38:28.830
Remember too that weaving
is grounded in the ordinary.

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:32.690
We are all at this moment
wearing something woven

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:36.550
or knitted or produced
through another textile form.

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:37.850
I'm hoping there might be people

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:40.100
who might actually be
knitting right now.

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:43.110
[Laughter] There is nothing
to be ashamed up in writing

00:38:43.110 --> 00:38:47.520
in straight forward language
in unpopular platforms

00:38:47.520 --> 00:38:48.910
that invite in people.

00:38:48.910 --> 00:38:51.060
From outside our field.

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:55.650
The everyday can be
powerful and compelling.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:58.470
For all of my fears
about whether,

00:38:58.470 --> 00:38:59.770
I'm not sure I have
that slide yet.

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:01.070
For all of my fears

00:39:01.070 --> 00:39:03.290
about whether my book was
reproducing a masculine

00:39:03.290 --> 00:39:04.590
printing history.

00:39:04.590 --> 00:39:07.360
I think I was worried
about the wrong thing.

00:39:07.360 --> 00:39:10.260
It's not the subject of
my book that is the key.

00:39:10.260 --> 00:39:12.030
But it's methodology.

00:39:12.030 --> 00:39:14.460
My feminist praxis
lies in opening

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:16.860
up the gates to a
field of study.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:20.170
In making complicated
abstract ideas understandable

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:22.900
and compelling, in
inviting those

00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:24.410
who have been outside the field.

00:39:24.410 --> 00:39:27.030
To move into its center.

00:39:27.030 --> 00:39:29.820
And unraveling and
remaking the warp

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:33.160
and weft of my own knowledge.

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:35.800
I'm so grateful to you
all for this opportunity

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:39.050
to rethink my own
scholarly practices.

00:39:39.050 --> 00:39:42.390
I hope this process of working
through what a feminist praxis

00:39:42.390 --> 00:39:45.810
of print history
might look like.

00:39:45.810 --> 00:39:48.040
Leads us all to think
about how we share

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:51.510
and open our field Thank you.

00:39:51.510 --> 00:40:00.840
[ Applause ]

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:03.730
&gt;&gt; So we have some time
for questions and answers.

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:06.220
So I will open up the
floor to questions.

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:07.830
&gt;&gt; I can't promise answers.

00:40:07.830 --> 00:40:09.130
I said I would take questions.

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:12.770
I didn't promise-- I'll try for
answers, if anybody had any.

00:40:17.210 --> 00:40:20.080
&gt;&gt; Well, I have sort of a
comment question [inaudible].

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:25.900
Alright? But I just was thinking
so much about all the threads

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:28.090
that you're weaving
for us today.

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:33.170
And thinking about the
book and printed word.

00:40:33.170 --> 00:40:34.470
And how those are reproduced.

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:39.630
And how even today we are
continue to reproduce even

00:40:39.630 --> 00:40:40.930
in new fields or research.

00:40:40.930 --> 00:40:42.990
Certain areas of
digital [inaudible].

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:47.820
So I'm wondering if you had
a couple of thoughts on that.

00:40:47.820 --> 00:40:52.390
And, and sort of ways of
pushing against some of that,

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:54.280
the embodiment of book history.

00:40:54.280 --> 00:41:01.470
As it's reproduced and
reanalyzed in new ways?

00:41:01.470 --> 00:41:03.040
So [inaudible].

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:05.810
&gt;&gt; So you know it's, it's.

00:41:05.810 --> 00:41:09.780
I'm never quite sure
what to do with books

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:11.960
and digital humanities.

00:41:11.960 --> 00:41:13.260
[Laughter] Right?

00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:14.560
And the other handful of
people I know who are in that,

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.150
you know interlocking space.

00:41:16.150 --> 00:41:19.930
Because on the one
hand there is a large

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:23.630
and important body
of work being done.

00:41:23.630 --> 00:41:26.370
On texts in digital humanities.

00:41:26.370 --> 00:41:28.720
In which you, you
know, you OCR on text.

00:41:28.720 --> 00:41:30.020
And you strip it out.

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:31.320
Then you do all sorts
of fun stuff

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:32.620
with it and it's important.

00:41:32.620 --> 00:41:34.830
And not my thing.

00:41:34.830 --> 00:41:38.990
But there is lots of interesting
work that can be done there.

00:41:38.990 --> 00:41:42.490
